AUDIO: 'up. It\'s not ready to run just yet. There are a few parts we will need to fill out manually. And there are a few risks you should be aware of when using community nad templates. Honestly, you\'ll probably never run into these, but they can happen, so it\'s worth a'

[06:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'quick heads up. The three main things to watch out for are trigger loops that can run endlessly, exposed API keys, especially inside HTTP requests, or just suspicious HTTP nodes that send data to unknown URLs. Avoiding these is pretty'

[06:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'straightforward. Just make sure triggers are set to run at reasonable intervals and don\'t get re-triggered. Double check any URLs data is being sent to and keep your API keys from getting exposed in requests. As I walk through this, I\'ll'

[06:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'go into each of those a little more in the parts where they could actually come up. Now, over on the left, you\'ll see instructions built into the workflow to guide setup. Not every template has it set up this nice, but a lot do, and it helps a ton. The first node is the'

[06:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'schedule trigger, and that actually brings up the first risk I mentioned a second ago. Accidental trigger loops or overly aggressive schedules. Right now, this is set to run every 30 minutes, which is way too often for this kind of workflow. I wouldn\'t want it creating'

[07:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and posting videos every half hour. or something like this, you\'d probably want to start with once per day, especially when you\'re triggering APIs that cost money like OpenAI or FAL. You want to be intentional about how often it runs or you\'ll burn through credits for no'

[07:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'reason. In this case, we\'re using a schedule trigger, which is easy to control, but about that looping risk I mentioned. Here\'s how that can happen. So, a loop usually occurs when a trigger is accidentally re-triggered by the workflow itself. For example, say you\'re'

[07:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'using a Google Sheets trigger that runs every time the sheet is updated. Then later in your workflow, you have a step that updates that same sheet. So maybe to mark a status from in progress to finished. If that update is misconfigured, like writing to a new row'

[07:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'instead of updating the existing one, it could trigger the workflow again and again and again. That\'s how you could end up in an infinite loop. Usually, this kind of thing shows up pretty obviously in testing, and it\'s easy to fix. But it\'s definitely something to'

[07:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
